(* Beginning of Notebook Content *)
Notebook[{

Cell[CellGroupData[{
Cell[TextData[{
 "OGRe: An ",
 StyleBox["O",
  FontWeight->Bold],
 "bject-Oriented ",
 StyleBox["G",
  FontWeight->Bold],
 "eneral ",
 StyleBox["Re",
  FontWeight->Bold],
 "lativity Package for Mathematica"
}], "Title",ExpressionUUID->"f27e3049-a969-c84e-b26c-426e7e1d0f98"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "By ",
 StyleBox["Barak Shoshany",
  FontWeight->Bold],
 "\nEmail: ",
 ButtonBox["baraksh@gmail.com",
  BaseStyle->"Hyperlink",
  ButtonData->{
    URL["mailto:baraksh@gmail.com"], None},
  ButtonNote->"mailto:baraksh@gmail.com"],
 "\nWebsite: ",
 ButtonBox["https://baraksh.com/",
  BaseStyle->"Hyperlink",
  ButtonData->{
    URL["https://baraksh.com/"], None},
  ButtonNote->"https://baraksh.com/"],
 "\nGitHub: ",
 ButtonBox["https://github.com/bshoshany",
  BaseStyle->"Hyperlink",
  ButtonData->{
    URL["https://github.com/bshoshany"], None},
  ButtonNote->"https://github.com/bshoshany"]
}], "Subtitle",ExpressionUUID->"5b4cb6c1-1ef2-d749-bd1c-f3500cac2cac"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Project GitHub repository: ",
 ButtonBox["https://github.com/bshoshany/OGRe",
  BaseStyle->"Hyperlink",
  ButtonData->{
    URL["https://github.com/bshoshany/OGRe"], None},
  ButtonNote->"https://github.com/bshoshany/OGRe"],
 "\nThis is the complete documentation for ",
 StyleBox["v2.0.0",
  FontWeight->Bold],
 " of the package, released on ",
 StyleBox["2026-05-02",
  FontWeight->Bold],
 "."
}], "Subsubtitle",ExpressionUUID->"337fa179-2ecd-da42-98c4-35c039dc9eb4"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Introduction", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"df64fcfe-c784-6748-b56c-574c2e297c05"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Overview", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"bab3d252-b06c-dd4e-bb3d-84e234c06a3d"],

Cell["\<\
OGRe is a modern Mathematica package for differential geometry and tensor \
calculus, designed to be both powerful and user-friendly. It can be used in a \
variety of contexts where tensor calculations are needed, in both mathematics \
and physics, but it is especially suitable for general relativity.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"925a3c98-9d7e-b14b-8e55-29e3df325dc3"],

Cell["\<\
Tensors are abstract objects, which can be represented as multi-dimensional \
arrays once a choice of index configuration and coordinate system is made. \
OGRe stays true to this definition, but takes away the complexities that come \
with combining tensors in different representations. This is done using an \
object-oriented programming approach, taking advantage of principles such as \
encapsulation and class invariants to eliminate the possibility of user error.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"0eaae90d-a937-f742-8d55-5921ad9bb6f2"],

Cell["\<\
The user initially defines each tensor in OGRe using its explicit components \
in any single representation. Operations on this tensor are then done \
abstractly, without needing to specify which representation to use. Possible \
operations include addition of tensors, multiplication of a tensor by a \
scalar, trace, contraction, and partial and covariant derivatives.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"f2456979-1479-8e4b-b813-1f13cff1d793"],

Cell["\<\
OGRe will automatically choose which representation to use for each tensor \
based on how the tensors are combined. For example, if two tensors are added, \
then OGRe will automatically use the same index configuration for both. \
Similarly, if two tensors are contracted, then OGRe will automatically ensure \
that the contracted indices are one upper (contravariant) and one lower \
(covariant). OGRe will also automatically transform all tensors being \
operated on to the same coordinate system.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"e073f9a9-1957-5e42-a841-bde2cbcdb5d6"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Transformations between representations are done behind the scenes; all the \
user has to do is specify which metric to use for raising and lowering \
indices, and how to transform between the coordinate systems being used. This \
also means that there is no room for user error. The user cannot mistakenly \
perform \"illegal\" operations such as ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"2", 
    SuperscriptBox[
     StyleBox["A", "TI"], "\[Mu]\[Nu]"], "+", 
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["B", "TI"], "\[Mu]\[Lambda]"], 
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["C", "TI"], "\[Lambda]\[Nu]"]}], TraditionalForm]],
  ExpressionUUID->"1c3670fc-b777-a64b-af16-203adca7c8c2"],
 ". Instead, the user simply inputs the names of the tensors, the order (but ",
 StyleBox["not",
  FontWeight->Bold],
 " the configuration) of indices for each, and the operations to perform - \
and the correct combination ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"2", 
    SuperscriptBox[
     StyleBox["A", "TI"], "\[Mu]\[Nu]"], 
    SubscriptBox[
     SuperscriptBox[
      StyleBox["B", "TI"], "\[Mu]"], "\[Lambda]"], 
    SuperscriptBox[
     StyleBox["C", "TI"], "\[Lambda]\[Nu]"]}], TraditionalForm]],
  ExpressionUUID->"d10250ee-04e2-d341-806e-f11d5efa83a4"],
 " will be automatically deduced."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"0d57586c-3f9a-374f-88b1-9abeae1aff65"],

Cell["\<\
I initially created OGRe for use in my own research, so I made it as flexible \
and powerful as possible. I also wanted my students to be able to use it \
easily and efficiently, even if they only have minimal experience with \
Mathematica and/or general relativity, so I made it simple to learn and easy \
to use. As a result, this package is equally suitable for both experienced \
and novice researchers.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"a9b947e0-fa60-cb43-a9a7-16cff332a738"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Features", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"a033f8d3-6491-b44b-99ad-58f31cb51157"],

Cell["\<\
Define coordinate systems and the transformation rules between them. Tensor \
components are then transformed automatically between coordinates behind the \
scenes as needed.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"9914c455-2fb4-8049-b322-a61123911334"],

Cell["\<\
Each tensor is associated with a specific metric. Tensor components are then \
transformed automatically between different index configurations, raising and \
lowering indices behind the scenes as needed.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"4df40238-b389-0848-b7d7-8493488904f1"],

Cell["\<\
Get the components of any tensor in any index configuration and coordinate \
system. Display or generate TeX code for the components, either in \
vector/matrix form or as a list of all unique non-zero elements. Metrics can \
also be displayed as a line element. Arbitrary functions or replacement rules \
can easily be applied to the components before they are displayed.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"b45cef62-aad4-3746-9181-e959b480a0f5"],

Cell["\<\
Automatically simplify tensor components, optionally with user-defined \
simplification functions and/or assumptions. Simplifications can be \
parallelized for a significant performance boost. The user may utilize the \
package's simplification algorithm for any Mathematica expression, not just \
tensors.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"b4d9c06b-a4e6-154b-b46e-e34c3fd87a47"],

Cell["\<\
Export tensors to a Mathematica notebook or to a file, so they can later be \
imported into another Mathematica session without having to redefine them \
from scratch.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"b28f2a4f-5143-5c4b-8b86-e76c1a02e4f7"],

Cell["\<\
Highly customizable. User settings are exported and imported along with the \
tensors. Some settings are persistent between sessions.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"3844765f-5ab1-6d40-9973-416b93a7c0ad"],

Cell["\<\
Easily calculate arbitrary tensor formulas using any combination of addition, \
multiplication by a scalar, trace, contraction, partial derivative, and \
covariant derivative.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"15046ff8-7497-9143-8756-fec8e51e6bd8"],

Cell["\<\
Built-in modules for calculating the Christoffel symbols (Levi-Civita \
connection), Riemann tensor, Ricci tensor and scalar, Kretschmann scalar, \
Einstein tensor, Weyl tensor, curve Lagrangian, and volume element from a \
metric.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"0be0b4a3-b379-e847-a96a-6773b2ac59ac"],

Cell["\<\
Calculate the norm-squared of tensors of any rank, and the determinant and \
volume element of any metric.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"1c5078eb-7ae0-1243-bf81-882ec4eb851e"],

Cell["\<\
Calculate the geodesic equations in terms of a user-defined affine curve \
parameter, in two different ways: from the Christoffel symbols or from the \
curve Lagrangian. For spacetime metrics, the geodesic equations can be \
calculated in terms of the time coordinate.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"ec57b576-fbc3-7943-a42f-50b438a02c96"],

Cell["\<\
Designed with speed and performance in mind, using optimized algorithms \
designed specifically for this package. Derived tensors are cached on first \
use to avoid recalculating.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"8d4ccc34-e3ca-614d-a579-9f3aa927e21e"],

Cell["\<\
Tensor IDs are auto-completed in the notebook interface when used with any \
suitable OGRe module, making the interface more user-friendly and easy to use.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"97f77e27-d423-1842-884a-ea4d986dd1b3"],

Cell["\<\
Fully portable. Can be imported directly from the web into any Mathematica \
notebook, without downloading or installing anything. Integrates seamlessly \
with the Wolfram Cloud.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"2fae6b4d-18d0-7240-8b90-a5548c5d1ed8"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Clear and detailed documentation, with many examples, in both ",
 ButtonBox["Mathematica notebook",
  BaseStyle->"Hyperlink",
  ButtonData->{
    URL["https://github.com/bshoshany/OGRe/blob/master/OGRe_Documentation.nb"]\
, None},
  ButtonNote->
   "https://github.com/bshoshany/OGRe/blob/master/OGRe_Documentation.nb"],
 " and ",
 ButtonBox["PDF",
  BaseStyle->"Hyperlink",
  ButtonData->{
    URL["https://github.com/bshoshany/OGRe/blob/master/OGRe_Documentation.\
pdf"], None},
  ButtonNote->
   "https://github.com/bshoshany/OGRe/blob/master/OGRe_Documentation.pdf"],
 " format. The notebook ",
 StyleBox["OGRe_Documentation.nb", "Input"],
 " can also be opened with the free ",
 ButtonBox["Wolfram Player",
  BaseStyle->"Hyperlink",
  ButtonData->{
    URL["https://www.wolfram.com/player/"], None},
  ButtonNote->"https://www.wolfram.com/player/"],
 ". Detailed usage messages are also provided."
}], "Item",ExpressionUUID->"24b85045-354f-104c-adfe-10493135bd84"],

Cell["\<\
Open source. The code is extensively documented; please feel free to fork and \
modify it as you see fit.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"b93333dc-2134-104a-8b69-5c0f435451dd"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Under continuous and active development. Bug reports and feature requests \
are welcome, and should be made via ",
 ButtonBox["GitHub issues",
  BaseStyle->"Hyperlink",
  ButtonData->{
    URL["https://github.com/bshoshany/OGRe/issues"], None},
  ButtonNote->"https://github.com/bshoshany/OGRe/issues"],
 "."
}], "Item",ExpressionUUID->"788f9aba-5e4d-3946-9e9f-b03196fcbcdf"],

Cell["\<\
Thoroughly tested. A comprehensive internal test suite thoroughly tests all \
OGRe modules and verifies that it accurately reproduces a wide variety of \
known results from differential geometry and general relativity, ensuring \
users can fully trust OGRe as a reliable tool for research and pedagogy.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"945ea581-188a-0849-8a00-93eae966f1c8"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["The object-oriented design philosophy", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"9f63807d-f217-0746-847c-28464e0922f9"],

Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["Object-oriented programming",
  FontWeight->Bold],
 " refers to a paradigm where a program's code is organized around objects. \
An ",
 StyleBox["object",
  FontWeight->Bold],
 " belongs to a user-defined type, called a ",
 StyleBox["class",
  FontWeight->Bold],
 ". The class defines the ",
 StyleBox["data",
  FontWeight->Bold],
 " that the object stores, as well as ",
 StyleBox["methods",
  FontWeight->Bold],
 " or ",
 StyleBox["member functions",
  FontWeight->Bold],
 " that read or manipulate that data. One of the fundamental principles of \
object-oriented programming is ",
 StyleBox["encapsulation",
  FontWeight->Bold],
 ", which means that the user may only access an object's data using the \
methods defined by the class, and is unable to access the object's data \
directly."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"4949d002-4506-9d44-a1e5-ea6d7742ba5e"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Importantly, encapsulation allows for the preservation of ",
 StyleBox["class invariants",
  FontWeight->Bold],
 ". An invariant is a condition of validity that can always be assumed to be \
satisfied by the data stored in each object. If the methods make sure to \
preserve the invariant whenever they store or manipulate the data, and the \
user is prevented from changing the data manually and thus potentially \
violating the invariant, then the implementation of the class can be greatly \
simplified, and performance can be improved, because we will not need to \
verify that the data is valid every time we perform an operation."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"58fbc07d-b1eb-194e-b87c-78ddc68222ed"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The main idea behind OGRe is to simplify the use of tensors by encoding all \
the information about a tensor in a single, self-contained object. As we \
mentioned above, a tensor is an abstract object. We can find components which \
represent this abstract entity in a particular coordinate system and index \
configuration, but the tensor is ",
 StyleBox["not",
  FontWeight->Bold],
 " its components. In OGRe, a tensor object is initially defined (or ",
 StyleBox["constructed",
  FontWeight->Bold],
 ") by providing the components of the tensor in a particular representation \
- but once this is done, the user does not need to worry about coordinates or \
indices anymore, or even remember which coordinates and indices were \
initially used. The abstract tensor object will automatically transform the \
initial data to a different coordinate system or index configuration as \
needed, based on the context in which it was used."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"ed1d0f32-a9ef-b646-8038-240052958baf"],

Cell["\<\
As a tensor object holds the components of the same tensor in many different \
representations, the most important class invariant is the assumption that \
the different components indeed represent the same tensor. This is achieved \
using encapsulation; the object's data can only be modified by private \
methods that preserve the invariant, and thus the user cannot accidentally \
cause a violation of the invariant by assigning components to one \
representation that are not related to the components of all other \
representations by the appropriate coordinate and/or index transformation.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"4ce52372-3630-1b4e-a62f-3bc6ca6ad1e9"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Unfortunately, Mathematica does not have built-in support for \
object-oriented programming. However, version 10.0 of Mathematica, released \
in 2014, introduced the ",
 StyleBox["Association", "Input"],
 " symbol. An ",
 StyleBox["Association", "Input"],
 " is an ",
 StyleBox["associative array",
  FontWeight->Bold],
 "; it is similar to a ",
 StyleBox["List", "Input"],
 ", except that instead of being just an array of values, an ",
 StyleBox["Association", "Input"],
 " is a list of keys with a value associated to each key. This allows us to \
easily implement a rudimentary form of object-oriented programming, storing \
the properties of each object in the keys of a corresponding ",
 StyleBox["Association", "Input"],
 "."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"55e71117-7a1c-3342-915c-c9630de5758d"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Of course, as Mathematica is not truly object-oriented, there is no actual \
\"tensor class\" defined anywhere in the package. Instead, the tensor class \
exists only ",
 StyleBox["implicitly",
  FontWeight->Bold],
 ", as a design paradigm. Furthermore, the functions that process the data \
stored in the tensor objects are not methods of a class, they are simply \
modules that take tensor objects as input and/or produce tensor objects as \
outputs. (In earlier versions, I tried using a syntax that resembled method \
syntax in languages such as C++ or Python, but eventually decided against it, \
as it was too cumbersome.) Still, designing the package with object-oriented \
programming in mind allows us to reap many of this paradigm's benefits, as \
explained above - and it simply makes sense for tensors, due to their \
abstract and multifaceted nature."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"1f7c18f9-a8a7-0941-93cf-7ff66758fa30"]
}, Open  ]]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Installing and loading the package", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"0af52315-4243-f643-825c-18f29a9368cd"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "This package is compatible with Mathematica 14.0 or later. It consists of \
only one file, ",
 StyleBox["OGRe.m", "Input"],
 ". There are several different ways to load the package:"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"dcccc674-3d53-ee49-80ea-756507443d70"],

Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["Run from local file with installation:",
  FontWeight->Bold],
 " This is the recommended option, as it allows you to permanently use the \
package offline from any Mathematica notebook. Download the file ",
 StyleBox["OGRe.m", "Input"],
 " from ",
 ButtonBox["the GitHub repository",
  BaseStyle->"Hyperlink",
  ButtonData->{
    URL["https://github.com/bshoshany/OGRe"], None},
  ButtonNote->"https://github.com/bshoshany/OGRe"],
 " and copy it to the directory given by ",
 StyleBox["FileNameJoin[{$UserBaseDirectory,\"Applications\"}]", "Input"],
 ". The package may now be loaded from any notebook by writing ",
 StyleBox["Needs[\"OGRe`\"]", "Input"],
 " (note the backtick ",
 StyleBox["`", "Input"],
 " following the word OGRe)."
}], "Item",ExpressionUUID->"e1bcaabc-5a16-3b4f-bf42-e171e410b714"],

Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["Run from local file without installation:",
  FontWeight->Bold],
 " This option allows you to use the package in a portable fashion, without \
installing it in the ",
 StyleBox["Applications", "Input"],
 " directory. Download the file ",
 StyleBox["OGRe.m", "Input"],
 " from ",
 ButtonBox["the GitHub repository",
  BaseStyle->"Hyperlink",
  ButtonData->{
    URL["https://github.com/bshoshany/OGRe"], None},
  ButtonNote->"https://github.com/bshoshany/OGRe"],
 ", place it in the same directory as the notebook you would like to use, and \
use the command ",
 StyleBox["Get[\"OGRe.m\",Path->NotebookDirectory[]]", "Input"],
 " to load the package."
}], "Item",ExpressionUUID->"2b74f870-5f25-3942-895a-3d6681995285"],

Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["Run from web with installation:",
  FontWeight->Bold],
 " This option allows you to automatically download and install the package \
on any computer. Simply run the command ",
 StyleBox["URLDownload[\"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/bshoshany/OGRe/\
master/OGRe.m\",FileNameJoin[{$UserBaseDirectory,\"Applications\",\"OGRe.m\"}]\
]", "Input"],
 " from any Mathematica notebook to permanently install the package. Then use \
",
 StyleBox["Needs[\"OGRe`\"]", "Input"],
 " from any notebook to load it."
}], "Item",ExpressionUUID->"25f3fe82-6df7-794d-97a9-dab7fd69ad42"],

Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["Run from web without installation:",
  FontWeight->Bold],
 " This option allows you to use the package from any Mathematica notebook on \
any computer, without manually downloading or installing it, as long as you \
have a working Internet connection. It also ensures that you always use the \
latest version of the package, but be aware that updates may sometimes not be \
fully backwards compatible. Simply write ",
 StyleBox["Get[\"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/bshoshany/OGRe/master/OGRe.\
m\"]", "Input"],
 " in any Mathematica notebook to load the package."
}], "Item",ExpressionUUID->"aabe489f-2095-d846-b5c8-fc12bb51d297"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Note: In the \"run from web\" options, if you wish to load a specific \
version for compatibility reasons, replace ",
 StyleBox["master", "Input"],
 " in the URL with the full version number including the ",
 StyleBox["v", "Input"],
 " prefix, e.g. ",
 StyleBox["https://raw.githubusercontent.com/bshoshany/OGRe/v2.0.0/OGRe.m", 
  "Input"],
 " for v2.0.0."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"2548b102-2643-2e43-8413-c684824e77ed"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "To ",
 StyleBox["uninstall",
  FontWeight->Bold],
 " the package, just delete the file from the ",
 StyleBox["Applications", "Input"],
 " directory, which can be done from within Mathematica using the command ",
 StyleBox["DeleteFile[FileNameJoin[{$UserBaseDirectory,\"Applications\",\"\
OGRe.m\"}]]", "Input"],
 "."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"6b83bd81-77db-8542-9288-4b608a3384a7"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Getting started", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"8d6191de-a30f-bd46-95cc-df1b321c3445"],

Cell["\<\
For the purposes of this documentation, I will use the \"run from local file \
without installation\" option, since you most likely downloaded both the \
documentation and the package together:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"2e244707-67f6-9c4c-a0b8-9b5cf8c477c4"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"Get", "[", 
  RowBox[{"\"\<OGRe.m\>\"", ",", 
   RowBox[{"Path", "\[Rule]", 
    RowBox[{"NotebookDirectory", "[", "]"}]}]}], "]"}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->"In[1]:=",ExpressionUUID->"d0c4f9ec-1e33-f44a-a048-a2accc988c62"],

Cell[BoxData[
 TagBox[GridBox[{
    {
     StyleBox[
      TemplateBox[{"\"OGRe: An \"", 
        StyleBox["\"O\"", Underlined, StripOnInput -> False], 
        "\"bject-Oriented \"", 
        StyleBox["\"G\"", Underlined, StripOnInput -> False], "\"eneral \"", 
        StyleBox["\"Re\"", Underlined, StripOnInput -> False], 
        "\"lativity Package for Mathematica\""},
       "RowDefault"],
      StripOnInput->False,
      FontSize->Larger,
      FontWeight->Bold]},
    {
     StyleBox[
      TemplateBox[{"\"By Barak Shoshany (\"", 
        TemplateBox[{"\"baraksh@gmail.com\"", "mailto:baraksh@gmail.com"}, 
         "HyperlinkURL"], "\") (\"", 
        TemplateBox[{"\"baraksh.com\"", "https://baraksh.com/"}, 
         "HyperlinkURL"], "\")\""},
       "RowDefault"],
      StripOnInput->False,
      FontWeight->Bold]},
    {
     StyleBox[
      TemplateBox[{"\"v2.0.0 (2026-05-02)\""},
       "RowDefault"],
      StripOnInput->False,
      FontWeight->Bold]},
    {
     StyleBox[
      TemplateBox[{"\"GitHub repository: \"", 
        TemplateBox[{
         "\"https://github.com/bshoshany/OGRe\"", 
          "https://github.com/bshoshany/OGRe"}, "HyperlinkURL"]},
       "RowDefault"],
      StripOnInput->False,
      FontWeight->Bold]},
    {
     StyleBox[
      TemplateBox[{"\"Release notes: \"", 
        TemplateBox[{
         "\"view on GitHub\"", 
          "https://github.com/bshoshany/OGRe/releases/tag/v2.0.0"}, 
         "HyperlinkURL"], "\" | \"", 
        ButtonBox[
         TagBox[
          
          PaneSelectorBox[{
           False -> StyleBox[
             "\"view in this notebook\"", "Hyperlink", StripOnInput -> False],
             True -> StyleBox[
             "\"view in this notebook\"", "HyperlinkActive", StripOnInput -> 
              False]}, 
           Dynamic[
            CurrentValue["MouseOver"]], ImageSize -> Automatic, FrameMargins -> 
           0], 
          MouseAppearanceTag["LinkHand"]], ButtonFunction :> 
         OGRe`Private`ShowReleaseNotesForTag["v2.0.0"], Appearance -> 
         "Frameless", BaseStyle -> "Hyperlink", Evaluator -> Automatic, 
         Method -> "Preemptive"]},
       "RowDefault"],
      StripOnInput->False,
      FontWeight->Bold]},
    {
     TemplateBox[{
      "\"\[Bullet] To view the full documentation for the package, type \"", 
       ButtonBox[
        TagBox[
         PaneSelectorBox[{
          False -> StyleBox[
            "\"TDocs[]\"", "Hyperlink", StripOnInput -> False], True -> 
           StyleBox["\"TDocs[]\"", "HyperlinkActive", StripOnInput -> False]}, 
          Dynamic[
           CurrentValue["MouseOver"]], ImageSize -> Automatic, FrameMargins -> 
          0], 
         MouseAppearanceTag["LinkHand"]], ButtonFunction :> OGRe`TDocs[], 
        Appearance -> "Frameless", BaseStyle -> "Hyperlink", Evaluator -> 
        Automatic, Method -> "Preemptive"], "\".\""},
      "RowDefault"]},
    {
     TemplateBox[{"\"\[Bullet] To list all available modules, type \"", 
       ButtonBox[
        TagBox[
         PaneSelectorBox[{
          False -> StyleBox[
            "\"?OGRe`*\"", "Hyperlink", StripOnInput -> False], True -> 
           StyleBox["\"?OGRe`*\"", "HyperlinkActive", StripOnInput -> False]}, 
          Dynamic[
           CurrentValue["MouseOver"]], ImageSize -> Automatic, FrameMargins -> 
          0], 
         MouseAppearanceTag["LinkHand"]], ButtonFunction :> 
        OGRe`Private`OGRePrint[
          Information["OGRe`*"]], Appearance -> "Frameless", BaseStyle -> 
        "Hyperlink", Evaluator -> Automatic, Method -> "Preemptive"], "\".\""},
      "RowDefault"]},
    {
     TemplateBox[{"\"\[Bullet] To get help on a particular module, type \"", 
       StyleBox["\"?\"", "Input", StripOnInput -> False], 
       "\" followed by the module name.\""},
      "RowDefault"]},
    {
     TemplateBox[{"\"\[Bullet] To enable parallelization, type \"", 
