Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Creating and displaying tensor objects", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"473857c4-a2e2-5b4f-b072-3ed03ab5d73a"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Defining coordinates", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"d0937561-0eb3-814b-a27a-c30cb7274780"],

Cell["\<\
To define tensors, we first need to define the manifold on which they reside. \
Since we are focusing on general relativity, we will use 4-dimensional \
spacetime manifolds in the following examples, but this package works equally \
well with manifolds that are purely spatial and/or have a different number of \
dimensions.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"654df86c-7c16-4346-9567-9ef5007db6aa"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The first step is to define the coordinate system. In OGRe, coordinates are \
represented as a special tensor object: a vector ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SuperscriptBox[
    StyleBox["x", "TI"], "\[Mu]"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "a1514eb6-feec-4a4f-8c12-b2308d8a7af2"],
 " (a tensor of rank 1) representing a point. To define the coordinates, we \
use the module ",
 StyleBox["TNewCoordinates", "Input"],
 ":"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"d785bc4c-f4fa-334b-a236-b5a5a53c928c"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"?", "TNewCoordinates"}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->"In[6]:=",ExpressionUUID->"e183c359-ef47-4d42-a25f-1153d85e094a"],

