and coordinate system.\\nTTeXList[\", Style[\"ID\", Bold], \", \", \
Style[\"indices\", Bold], \"] returns the components in the index \
configuration \", Style[\"indices\", Bold], \", which should be a list of the \
form {\\[PlusMinus]1, \\[PlusMinus]1, ...}, where +1 corresponds to an upper \
index and -1 corresponds to a lower index.\\nTTeXList[\", Style[\"ID\", \
Bold], \", \", Style[\"coordinatesID\", Bold], \"] returns the components in \
the coordinate system \", Style[\"coordinatesID\", Bold], \".\\nTTeXList[\", \
Style[\"ID\", Bold], \", \", Style[\"rules\", Bold], \"] applies \
ReplaceAll[\", Style[\"rules\", Bold], \"] to each of the tensor's elements, \
and then automatically simplifies them, before they are converted to TeX. \", \
Style[\"rules\", Bold], \" can be either a single rule of the form \", Style[\
\"lhs \\[Rule] rhs\", Bold], \" or a list of rules.\\nTTeXList[\", Style[\"ID\
\", Bold], \", \", Style[\"function\", Bold], \"] maps \", \
Style[\"function\", Bold], \" to each of the tensor's elements, and then \
automatically simplifies them, before they are converted to \
TeX.\\nTTeXList[\", Style[\"ID\", Bold], \", \", Style[\"indices\", Bold], \
\", \", Style[\"coordinatesID\", Bold], \", \", Style[\"rules\", Bold], \", \
\", Style[\"function\", Bold], \"] does all of the above; any of the \
arguments can be omitted. If both \", Style[\"rules\", Bold], \" and \", \
Style[\"function\", Bold], \" are given, the rules will be applied before the \
function.\\nUse TSetExactSignChecks to enable or disable exact sign checks. \
When exact sign checks are enabled (the default), if TTeXList cannot detect \
equality of two components up to sign by direct comparison, it checks whether \
the sum of the components can be proven to equal zero, which may require \
simplification. For tensors with complicated components, this may take a long \
time, in which case this option can be disabled; however, TTeXList will then \
only be able to detect when two components are the same up to sign in simple \
cases.\\nNote: It is recommended to use CopyToClipboard@TTeXList[...] to copy \
the resulting TeX string to the clipboard directly.\"]]]]\)", "Documentation" -> 
